        <p>
          Determining an Estimated Due Date (EDD) is essential for monitoring fetal development, tracking critical checkpoints, and scheduling key clinical evaluations:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-4 flex flex-col gap-1 text-slate font-medium">
          <li><strong>Naegele's Rule (LMP):</strong> The standard formula calculates the due date by adding 280 days (40 weeks) to the first day of the last menstrual period. If your menstrual cycle is longer or shorter than the standard 28-day model, clinical models adjust this offset accordingly.</li>
          <li><strong>Conception Date:</strong> Conception typically occurs approximately 14 days after the LMP in standard 28-day cycles. Dating from a known conception date adds exactly 266 days (38 weeks) to find the due date.</li>
          <li><strong>IVF Transfer:</strong> Due dates for pregnancies achieved via In Vitro Fertilization (IVF) are highly precise. Calculations are adjusted for the age of the embryo at transfer: adding 261 days for Day 5 transfers or 263 days for Day 3 transfers.</li>
          <li><strong>Ultrasound Dating:</strong> Measurement of the fetus (crown-rump length) in the early first trimester is considered the most clinically accurate method for dating, particularly when cycles are irregular.</li>
